4 Section 3. That § 13-16-6.4 be AMENDED:
5 13-16-6.4. Approval Except as otherwise provided in this section, approval to
6 enter into an agreement or issue capital outlay certificates pursuant to § 13-16-6.3 is
7 subject to a referendum if five percent of the registered voters, based upon the total
8 number of registered voters at the last preceding general election, petition, within twenty
9 days thereafter, to have the question of approval to enter into the agreement or issue
10 capital outlay certificates placed upon the ballot at a. The board of a school district may
11 issue capital outlay certificates pursuant to §§ 13-16-6.2 and 13-16-6.3, with a maturity
12 date in excess of ten years from the date of issuance, only if the question of issuing the
13 capital outlay certificates is approved by the voters of the district.
14 A special election called for that purpose and the purposes provided in this section
15 must be held on:
16 (1) The first Tuesday after the first Monday in March;
17 (2) The first Tuesday after the first Monday in June; or
18 (3) The first Tuesday after the first Monday in November.
19 If the bond election is held on a date listed in subdivision (2) or (3) in an even-
20 numbered year, the election must be held in conjunction with the regular primary or
21 general election, respectively. When the election is held in conjunction with the primary
22 or general election, the expenses and governmental responsibilities of a combined election
23 must be shared in a manner agreed upon by the board of the school district and the boards
24 of county commissioners involved.
25 The business manager shall give notice that the question is to be on the ballot at
26 the regular or special election, as provided by law for school elections, and prepare official
27 ballots therefor according to the provisions of this title. Approval of the question to enter
28 into an agreement or issue capital outlay certificates requires an affirmative vote of at
29 least sixty percent of those voting on the question.
30 If the question submitted to the voters at an election is not approved by the voters,
31 the school board may, by resolution, place the question on the ballot at the next available
32 election provided by this section.
